1 It was already the hour that turns the desire
2 of sailors to the shore and melts their heart
3 on the day they have said farewell to their sweet friends;

4 and that pierces the new pilgrim of love
5 if he hears a bell in the distance
6 that seems to mourn the dying day;

13 ‘Te lucis ante’ so devoutly
14 issued from her mouth and with such sweet notes
15 that it made me lose my mind;

22 I saw that gentle host
23 then silently look upward,
24 as if waiting, pale and humble;

34 I could clearly discern their blond heads;
35 but my eyes were confounded in their faces,
36 like a faculty that is overwhelmed by too much.

43 And Sordello also: “Now let us descend
44 among the great shades, and we will speak to them;
45 it will be pleasing to them to see you greatly.”

55 No beautiful greeting was left unspoken between us;
56 then he asked: “How long is it since you came
57 to the foot of the mountain by the distant waters?”

94 As he was speaking, Sordello drew him to himself,
95 saying: “See our adversary over there”;
96 and he pointed his finger so that he would look there.

103 I did not see, and therefore cannot say,
104 how the celestial hawks moved;
105 but I did see both of them in motion.

